children.name: wet a2
children.definition: wet if sth iswet,it has a lot of liquid on it or in it; if sb iswet,their clothes, skin, and hair are wet:
examples: i can’t come out yet - my hair’s still wet.
you’d better change out of those wet clothes.
let’s not sit here - the grass is wet.
freshly wet roads are dangerous because oil and dust mix with the water to make them slippery.
get wet
hurry up with the umbrella - i’m getting wet!
all wetinformal
when he got out of the boat, the sleeves of his sweater were all wet.
wet paint/ inkthat has not yet dried
all the benches had been painted and had ‘wet paint’ signs on them.

children.name: soggy x
children.definition: soggy sth that issoggyis softer than usual and looks or feels unpleasant, because it has become wet:ướt sũng
examples: breakfast was terrible - the eggs were burnt and the toast was soggy.
a soggy pile of old leaves lay in the corner of the yard.

children.name: soaked b2
children.definition: soaked very wet all the way through: ướt đầm
examples: your clothes are soaked. leave them in front of the fire to dry.
don’t leave the cushions in the garden. they’ll get soaked if it rains.
soaked with
panting and soaked with sweat, ron came running into the house.
soaked to the skin
when the men came in from the storm, they were soaked to the skin.
soaked throughextremely wet
after a morning walk through the meadow, my shoes were completely soaked through.

children.name: soaking wet b2
children.definition: soaking wet / sopping wet / dripping wet/wringing wet  sb or sth that issoaking wetetc is so wet that drops of water fall from them:
examples: we were soaking wet by the time we got out of the rain.
there’s no way i can wear this shirt tonight - it’s still sopping wet.
can i call you back in five minutes? i just got out of the shower and i’m dripping wet.

children.name: soaking b2
children.definition: soaking  sb who issoakingis very wet, so that drops of water fall from their clothes or hair:
examples: you’re soaking. take those wet clothes off before you catch a cold.
someone had pushed sally into the swimming pool, and she was soaking.

children.name: drenched x
children.definition: drenched if a person or area isdrenched,it is completely wet, because a lot of rain or water has poured onto them: ướt sũng,ướt sạch
examples: everyone got completely drenched when a huge wave hit the boat.
the two and a half hour walk in the wind and rain left us drenched.
the athletes were drenchedin/withsweat.

children.name: sodden x
children.definition: sodden especially uk (of something which can absorb water) very wet and heavy, and is usually spoiled because there is so much water in it: ướt sũng, ướt đầm
examples: his shoes were sodden and covered with mud.
mary tried to read the writing in her sodden address book, but it was impossible.

children.name: saturated x
children.definition: saturated sth that issaturatedis so wet that it cannot hold any more water or liquid: “no, bão hoà”
examples: when the summer rains begin, the soil quickly becomes saturated.
saturated with
the bandage around his knee was already saturated with blood.

children.name: waterlogged x
children.definition: waterlogged (of land) full of water and almost covered by a layer of it, or (of a boat) full of water and therefore unable to keep moving or floating : úng nước; đẫm nước; ngập nước
examples: the game was cancelled because the field was waterlogged.
you can plant the seeds anytime, as long as the soil is not frozen or waterlogged.
unfortunately the game was cancelled because of a waterlogged ukpitch/ usfield.

children.name: awash x
children.definition: awashwrittenif a floor or area isawash,it is covered with a lot of water: ngập nước
examples: the ship leaned further to starboard and soon the decks were awash.
awash with/in
the toilet leaks, leaving the bathroom floor awash in slimy water.

children.name: look like a drowned rat x
children.definition: look like a drowned rat informal to be very wet, especially because you have been in heavy rain:ướt như chuột lột
examples: she arrived at the church looking like a drowned rat

children.name: to make sb or sth wet
get sth wet u
children.definition: get sth wet especiallyspokento make sth wet, especially by not taking enough care to keep it dry:để cái gì bị ướt
examples: don’t splash me - i don’t want to get my hair wet.
how did you manage to get the bathroom floor so wet?
she can’t wash the dishes without getting the front of her clothes all wet.

children.name: wet x
children.definition: wet to deliberately put water or other liquid onto sth:làm ướt
examples: the other hairdresser usually wets my hair before she cuts it.
she wet her index finger and cleaned the spot off the mirror.
wetting the toothbrush before you put the toothpaste on makes the bristles softer.

children.name: soak c1
children.definition: soak if yousoaksth, you leave it in water for a long time in order to make it clean, soft etc. if water or another liquidsoakssth, it makes it very wet: ngâm/ làm ướt đẫm
examples: soak the beans overnight before cooking.
the rain had come in through the bottom of our tent and completely soaked our clothes.
soak sth in sth
soak a piece of cotton in water and use it to clean the wound.

children.name: drench x
children.definition: drench to make sb or sth extremely wet with a large amount of water:
examples: he turned the hose on us and drenched us all.
blood was pouring from the cut, drenching his shirt.
a sudden thunderstorm had drenched usto the skin.
the athletes were drenchedin/withsweat.

children.name: swamp x
children.definition: swamp tosuddenlycover sth completely with a large amount of water, especially in a way thatcausesdamage: “đầm lầy”
examples: water the young plants well, but don’t swamp them.
the dam burst, swamping the valley and hundreds of homes.
about 3000 years ago a tidal wave swamped the coastal lowlands of greece, causing massive destruction.

children.name: saturate x
children.definition: saturate to completely cover or fill sth with liquid, so that it is wet all the way through: “no, bão hoà”, làm ướt sũng, thấm đẫm
examples: heavy rains had saturated the ground, turning the streets into rivers.
saturate the label with vinegar and let it sit before you try to scrape it off the bottle.
he had cut his leg badly, and his trousers were saturatedwith/inblood.

children.name: damp b2
children.definition: damp slightly wet, especially in an unpleasant way:ẩm
examples: don’t put that shirt on. it’s still damp.
clean the counter with a damp cloth.
be careful you don’t slip - the grass is damp.
there was a damp spot on the ceiling.

children.name: moist x
children.definition: moist  sth that ismoistis slightly wet, especially in a good way:ẩm
examples: the mixture should be slightly moist, but not sticky.
water the plants regularly to keep the soil moist
the sandwiches are made with moist slices of chicken breast, topped with various ingredients

children.name: clammy x
children.definition: clammy sth that isclammy, especially sb’s skin, is slightly wet and feels unpleasantly cold and sticky: ẩm ướt
examples: as soon as the interview began, i felt my hands go clammy.
we were left waiting in our clammy clothes for over an hour.
clammy with
his whole body was clammy with sweat as a result of the malaria.

children.name: dampen x
children.definition: dampen to make sth slightly wet by putting a little water on it: làm ẩm
examples: dampen the soil a little before you put the seeds in.
she dampened a cloth and held it to his forehead.
if you dampen your piece of paper before you start painting it will be easier to paint evenly.

children.name: moisten x
children.definition: moisten/ˈmɔɪsən/  to make something slightly wet by putting a small amount of water or another liquid on it, especially to stop it from getting too dry:
examples: ▪ add just enough water to moisten the cake mixture without making it too watery.
▪ tom paused and moistened his lips.
▪ when the clay becomes dry, moisten it lightly before you continue to shape it.
moistenverb[ i or t ] thành ra ẩm ướt/ ( ai )làm ẩm, dấp nước( cai gi )
to make something slightly wet or to become slightly wet
_moisten the cloth before using it to clean glass.
_moisten the clay if it seems too dry.
_shemoistenedherlips(= made her lips wet with her tongue ).

children.name: wet b1
children.definition: wetdescribes paint, ink, or a similar substance when it has not had time to dry and become hard: chưa khô; còn ướt; còn tươi
examples: the paint's still wet.
a notice saying 'wet paint!'

children.name: damp b2
children.definition: damp dampairorweatheris slightly wet in an unpleasant way, and makes you feel cold: ẩm thấp, ẩm ướt
examples: it’s cold and damp outside - make sure you wear a warm coat.
at first i hated the damp weather in britain.
damp/dampness[u]
the constant cold and damp made tony feel even worse.

children.name: wet a2
children.definition: wet if the weather is wet, it rains a lot.wetandrainymean the same and are used in the same way : ẩm ướt
examples: in cyprus during the winter, you’ll only have the occasional wet day.
the wet weather is expected to continue.
another wet summer
it's been wet all week.
you should bring a waterproof jacket and strong boots in case of wet weather.

children.name: dank x
children.definition: dank air that isdank,especially the air in an enclosed room or space, is unpleasantly wet and cold and smells bad: ẩm ướt; ướt át; nhớp nháp
examples: the air in the room was heavy and dank, and i couldn’t sleep.
i’m not surprised he’s miserable, living in that dank old house.
the bag had been sitting in a dank tent for three days and smelled like an old laundry hamper.
a dank, dark cellar
in the cathedral vaults the air was dank and stale.

children.name: rainy b1
children.definition: rainy if the weather is rainy, it rains a lot:ẩm, mưa nhiều
examples: a coldrainy dayin october
i haterainy weather.
the rainy seasonis in july.
a rainy weekend in november
the weather continued to be rainy.

children.name: drizzly x
children.definition: drizzlyraining slightly, with a lot of mist in the air ::có mưa phùn
examples: a drizzly afternoon
drizzly weather
the morning was grey and drizzly.

children.name: showery x
children.definition: showery raining for short periods : thường có mưa rào
examples: the cool, bright, showery weather of early april
the weather will be showery, with some sunny intervals.
